SIMPLE: indicative
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indicative
<hw>In*dic"a*tive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indicativus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>indicatif</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Pointing out; bringing to notice; giving intimation
or knowledge of something not visible or obvious.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That truth is productive of utility, and utility
<qex>indicative</qex> of truth, may be thus proved.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Warburton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>Suggestive; representing the
whole by a part, as a fleet by a ship, a forest by a tree,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Indicative mood</b></col> <fld>(Gram.)</fld>, <cd>that
mood or form of the verb which indicates, that is, which simply affirms
or denies or inquires; <as>as, he <examp>writes</examp>; he <examp>is
not writing</examp>; <examp>has</examp> the mail
<examp>arrived</examp>?</as></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indicative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Indicative
<hw>In*dic"a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The
indicative mood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indicatively</ent>⟦br⟧
